unning out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Slot A: \"500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.\" Slot B: real-infra/OS resource boundary (actual process memory and wall-clock behavior under load). Slot C: if lowered to Integration, mocked clocks/in-memory fakes can pass while the real process OOMs or breaches timeout due to allocator/GC/IO behavior. Final label: System because OS-level memory and timing behavior are decisive, and one-level-lower tests can hide those failures.","test_description":"Execute the pipeline as a real process against a generated 500k-row CSV and real runtime limits (timeout + memory observation), then assert completion within configured timeout and no OOM/kill event.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the S3 bucket returns a transient 503 error, the pipeline retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.\" Slot B: handoff between ingest client, retry policy, and batch orchestrator state. Slot C: if lowered to Unit, retry helper tests can pass while orchestration still aborts the batch on first retryable error. Rejection gate for System: no behavior text requires real network/S3 service characteristics beyond handling a retryable 503 and backoff policy, which can be exercised with wired modules and controlled fakes. Final label: Integration because orchestration handoff is decisive, and Unit can miss batch-level retry behavior.","test_description":"Wire real pipeline retry/orchestration modules with a fake S3 adapter that returns 503 for first N attempts then success; use a controllable clock to verify exponential backoff intervals and assert batch eventually succeeds without full-batch failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Rows successfully written to PostgreSQL are not duplicated if the pipeline is restarted mid-batch.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Slot A: \"not duplicated if the pipeline is restarted mid-batch.\" Slot B: real-infra boundary requiring process restart semantics plus real DB durability/idempotency behavior. Slot C: if lowered to Integration, same-process re-invocation can miss restart-specific bugs (checkpoint flush timing, transaction visibility, crash window) that create duplicates after an actual restart. Final label: System because restart + durable store behavior is decisive, and Integration can miss duplicate-creation on real restart boundaries.","test_description":"Run pipeline against a real PostgreSQL instance, force termination mid-batch after some commits, restart the process, and assert final table contains exactly one copy per logical row (using key/count checks) with no duplicates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
